        "This is a two-part drawing day: a labeled skeleton and a lever diagram of one joint. Use the labeled skeleton and biceps/triceps reference images to check accuracy, but have the child draw from memory first wherever possible — the act of recalling the shape and reaching for the right word (humerus, not “arm bone”) is what fixes the vocabulary for the rest of the unit, since this map will be referenced again and again.",
        "The lever diagram continues directly from yesterday's forearm work: label fulcrum (elbow), force (bicep insertion), and load (hand), and note which lever class it represents. For Form IIA, push further into the trade-off question — why is a speed-for-force trade useful for a creature that uses tools, writes, and reaches? That question quietly points toward the human capacity for skilled work, not just brute strength.",
